{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians --> | name = China Forbes | image = ChinaForbes.jpg | image_size = 250 | landscape = yes | caption = Forbes with Pink Martini in concert, 2014 | background = solo_singer | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|4|29}} | birth_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], Massachusetts, U.S. | genre = | occupation = Singer, songwriter | years_active = | label = [[Heinz Records|Heinz]] | associated_acts =[[Pink Martini]] | website = {{URL|www.chinaforbes.com}} }}
'''China Forbes''' (born April 29, 1970) is an American singer and songwriter who has been the lead singer of the band [[Pink Martini]] since 1995.
==Life and career== The daughter of Peggy (née Woodford) and Donald Cameron Forbes, China Forbes was born and raised in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], Massachusetts.<ref name="meet">{{cite web|url=http://www.pinkmartini.com/band/pm_band.html|title=Meet the Band|publisher=Pinkmartini.com|accessdate=November 12, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718062237/http://www.pinkmartini.com/band/pm_band.html|archivedate=July 18, 2012|df=}}</ref> Her father was of French and Scottish descent, and her mother is African-American.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jane Cornwell|date=April 24, 2008|work=The Telegraph|title=The Pink Martini girl gets serious|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/3672840/The-Pink-Martini-girl-gets-serious.html|accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bill Cribbs|url=http://www.genealogybuff.com/ma/harvard/webbbs_config.pl/noframes/read/71|title=Harvard University Obituary and Death Notice Collection - 71|publisher=Genealogybuff.com|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> She attended [[Phillips Exeter Academy]] ('88),<ref>{{cite news|author=Bill Ewing|title=China Forbes '88: Finding Her Own Voice|work=The Exeter Bulletin|date=Winter 2002|url=http://exeter.edu/documents/Exeter_Bulletin/alumni_profiles/forbes_88.htm|accessdate=June 6, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040537/http://exeter.edu/documents/Exeter_Bulletin/alumni_profiles/forbes_88.htm|archivedate=March 4, 2016|df=}}</ref> then studied visual arts at [[Harvard University]],<ref name="meet"/> where she met [[Thomas Lauderdale]], a classically trained pianist.<ref name="uk">[https://www.theguardian.com/arts/features/story/0,11710,1462223,00.html Speaking in tongues], an April 2005 article about Forbes and Pink Martini from ''[[The Guardian]]'' {{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/arts/features/story/0,11710,1462223,00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-04-18 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050418051918/http://www.guardian.co.uk/arts/features/story/0,11710,1462223,00.html |archivedate=April 18, 2005 |df= }}</ref> They became friends and met regularly to play music together.<ref name="uk"/> At Harvard, she won the Jonathan Levy Prize for acting.
After graduating in 1992, Forbes worked as an actress for several years, performing [[Off-Broadway]] in New York City. She then became a musician, forming a band and recording a solo album. She sang the song "Ordinary Girl" for the television series ''[[Clueless (TV series)|Clueless]]'' and "[[Que Sera, Sera (Whatever Will Be, Will Be)|Que Sera Sera]]" over the credits for the movie ''[[In the Cut]]''.<ref name="meet"/> While living in Portland, Oregon, Lauderdale asked her to sing with [[Pink Martini]], a band he had assembled to play at political fundraisers. After three years commuting from New York, she moved to Portland in 1998 to work full-time with the band.<ref name="uk"/> Forbes and Lauderdale co-wrote the band's hit "Sympathique (Je ne Veux Pas Travailler)" among many other band originals.
Apart from her work with Pink Martini, she has released solo albums, including ''Love Handle'' (November 1995) and ''{{'}}78'' ([[Heinz Records|Heinz]]2008) which includes her song "Hey Eugene" in its original version. She is featured on [[Michael Feinstein]]'s album ''[[The Sinatra Project]]'', singing a duet of "How Long Will It Last?"<ref name="feinstein">{{cite news|author=Stephen Holden|date=August 31, 2008|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/01/arts/music/01fein.html|title=Feinstein Comes Full Swing to Capitol-Era Sinatra|accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref> She recorded two songs in French with [[Georges Moustaki]] for his album ''Solitaire''.
On June 21, 2011, Pink Martini announced that Forbes was taking an extended leave of absence for at least one year for surgery on her vocal cords. She made a full recovery and was back on stage with the band within 5 months. Forbes is thanked in the liner notes to ''[[1969 (Pink Martini album)|1969]]'', the band's album with Japanese vocalist [[Saori Yuki]].{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
She is a cousin of U.S. Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] and indie-rock musician [[Ed Droste]] of [[Grizzly Bear (band)|Grizzly Bear]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/3672840/The-Pink-Martini-girl-gets-serious.html|title=The Pink Martini girl gets serious|publisher=Telegraph|date=April 24, 2008|accessdate=November 12, 2015}}</ref> Her sister is [[Maya Forbes]], a screenwriter and director. Maya's movie ''[[Infinitely Polar Bear]]'' (2014) was inspired by events from childhood.<ref name="LA-times">{{cite news|author=John Horn|title=Maya Forbes revisits her childhood in 'Infinitely Polar Bear'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2014/jan/21/entertainment/la-et-mn-sundance-polar-20140122|work=Los Angeles Times|date=January 21, 2014|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>
