{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}} {{Infobox officeholder |name = Hussein Al Oweini |image = حسين العويني.jpg |imagesize = |office1 =Interim [[List of Prime Ministers of Lebanon|Prime Minister of Lebanon]] |term_start1 = 14 February 1951 |term_end1 = 7 April 1951 |president1 = [[Bechara El Khoury]] |predecessor1 = [[Riad Al Solh]] |successor1 = [[Abdullah Yafi|Abdullah Arif Yafi]] |office =18th [[List of Prime Ministers of Lebanon|Prime Minister of Lebanon]] |term_start = 20 February 1964 |term_end = 25 July 1965 |president = [[Charles Helou]] |predecessor = [[Rashid Karami]] |successor = Rashid Karami |birth_date = {{birth date|1900|12|24|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Beirut]], [[Ottoman Empire]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1971|12|10|1900|12|24|df=y}} |death_place = [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]] |spouse = |children = |religion = [[Islam]] |party = |alma_mater = }}
'''Hussein Al Oweini''' (24 December 1900 – 10 December 1971)<ref>https://www.rulers.org/indexo.html</ref><ref>http://www.islamguiden.com/kvinnor/index518.htm</ref> was a [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] businessman and politician, who served as prime minister of [[Lebanon]] for two times. He also held other cabinet positions.
==Early life== Oweini was born in 1900.<ref name=jlibrary>{{cite web|title=Rulers of Lebanon|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/arabs/lebrule.html|work=Jewish Library|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref> He was a member of a Sunni family from [[Beirut]].<ref name=Dekmejian1975>{{cite book|author=R. Hrair Dekmejian|title=Patterns of Political Leadership: Egypt, Israel, Lebanon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MCVgiW9KDh8C&pg=PA33|accessdate=8 April 2013|year=1975|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-87395-291-0|page=33}}</ref>
==Career== Oweini went to [[Saudi Arabia]] and worked as a business agent for [[Saudi royal family|the Saudi royal family]] from 1923 to 1947.<ref name=saad9july>{{cite news|last=Mehio|first=Saad|title=Prime Minister Alwaleed bin Talal? For what?|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Politics/Jul/09/Prime-Minister-Alwaleed-bin-Talal-For-what.ashx#axzz2ZQEiKeb1|accessdate=18 July 2013|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=9 July 2002}}</ref> He also founded a company, Ne'ma Te'ma, in [[Riyadh]].<ref name=ain21apr>{{cite news|title=Riyadh's guest |url=http://www.ainalyaqeen.com/issues/20000421/feat1en.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130628092901/http://www.ainalyaqeen.com/issues/20000421/feat1en.htm |dead-url=yes |archive-date=28 June 2013 |accessdate=8 April 2013 |work=Ain Al Yaqeen |date=21 April 2000 }}</ref> He served as [[Prime Minister of Lebanon]] for two times. He was first appointed prime minister on 14 February 1951 under president [[Bechara El Khoury]]<ref name=Dekmejian1975/><ref name=was14june>{{cite news|last=Mroueh|first=Wassim|title=Looking back on almost 7 decades of Cabinet crises |url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Politics/2011/Jun-14/Looking-back-on-almost-7-decades-of-Cabinet-crises.ashx#axzz2PtI5l2yM|accessdate=8 April 2013|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=14 June 2011|location=Beirut}}</ref> and replaced [[Riad Al Solh]] in the post. He was in office until 7 April 1951 and succeeded by [[Abdullah Yafi|Abdullah Arif Yafi]].<ref name=jlibrary/> On 27 September 1957, Oweini and two other former prime ministers, namely [[Saeb Salam]] and Abdullah Yufi, were arrested on charges of planning an armed coup and riots during [[Lebanese general election, 1957|the elections]] held in May.<ref name=Khalaf2002>{{cite book|author=Samir Khalaf|title=Civil and Uncivil Violence in Lebanon: A History of the Internationalization of Communal Contact|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=10R4ol9rSuAC&pg=PA111|accessdate=8 April 2013|year=2002|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-50536-9|page=111}}</ref>
Oweini's second term as prime minister was from 20 February 1964 to 25 July 1965 under president [[Charles Helou]].<ref name=enews2dec>{{cite news|last=Cornell|first=George W.|title=Welcome Pope|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=mfpiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qm0NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1623,185065&dq=hussein+al+oweini&hl=en|accessdate=8 April 2013|newspaper=The Evening News|date=2 December 1964|agency=AP|location=Bombay}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bridge stamps of Lebanon|url=http://www.bridgeguys.com/SGlossary/StampsLebanon.html|work=Bridge Guys|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref> Both his predecessor and successor was [[Rashid Karami]] as prime minister.<ref name=jlibrary/> Oweini was the leader of the National Front.<ref name=wyn22july>{{cite news|last=Wynn|first=Wilton|title=Lebanon leader predicts US troop removal|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=860&dat=19580722&id=n5laAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Z0sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5423,737149|accessdate=8 April 2013|newspaper=Ellensburg Daily Record|date=22 July 1958|agency=AP|location=Beirut}}</ref> He also served as foreign minister of Lebanon for three times; from 1958 to 1960, in 1965 and from 1968 to 1969.<ref name=rulers1>{{cite web|title=Foreign ministers|url=http://rulers.org/fm3.html|work=Rulers|accessdate=8 April 2013}}</ref> During his third term as foreign minister, Oweini was also defense minister, since the cabinet was a four-man body led by Prime Minister Abdullah Yafi.<ref name=dis2jan>{{cite news|title=New peace plan for Middle East offered|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=740bAAAAIBAJ&sjid=R1EEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4705,453580&dq=hussein+al+oweini&hl=en|accessdate=8 April 2013|newspaper=The Dispatch|date=2 January 1969|agency=UPI}}</ref>
==Death== Oweini died on 10 December 1971, aged 70.<ref name=rulers1/>
==Legacy== For his memory an award, Hussein Al Oweini award, is being given.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zahraa Shaito|url=http://www.aub.edu.lb/fas/pspa/people/Pages/shaito.aspx|publisher=American University of Beirut|accessdate=18 July 2013}}</ref>
