{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}
:''For other people named John Adair, see [[John Adair (disambiguation)]].''

Professor '''John Eric<ref>[[Chambers Biographical Dictionary]], 1990, p. 8</ref> Adair''' (born 18 May 1934) is a British academic who is a [[leadership]] theorist and author of more than forty books (translated into eighteen languages) on business, military and other leadership.<ref name="Professor John Adair">[http://www.windsorleadershiptrust.org.uk/en/1/jadair.html/ Professor John Adair]</ref>

==Life==
Adair was born in [[Luton]] and educated at [[St Paul's School (London)|St Paul's School]] before undertaking his [[National Service]] as a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[Scots Guards]] from 1953 to 1955.  Unusually, he served as [[adjutant]] of a [[Bedouin]] regiment in the [[Arab Legion]]<ref>[http://forum.mpacuk.org/showthread.php?p=698785/ John Adair in the Arab Legion]</ref> and was briefly in command of the garrison of Jerusalem in the front line.<ref name="Professor John Adair"/> He also studied at [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] Nautical College (where he qualified as an Arctic trawler [[deckhand]] in 1955) and [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]], obtaining his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1959.  He later obtained a doctorate from [[King's College London]] in 1966 and a [[Degrees of the University of Oxford#Bachelors' degrees|BLitt]] degree from [[Jesus College, Oxford]] in 1971.  He became a [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal Historical Society]] in 1966.  After working as a Senior Lecturer at the [[Royal Military Academy, Sandhurst]] from 1961 to 1967, he later worked for the [[The Industrial Society|Industrial Society]] before becoming Professor of [[Leadership Studies]] at the [[University of Surrey]] in 1979, a post he held until 1984.  He was a visiting professor at the [[University of Exeter]] from 1990 to 2000.  He is currently an Emeritus Fellow of the Windsor Leadership Trust where he regularly speaks on Leadership development programmes. Since 2006, he has been Honorary Professor of Leadership at the China Executive Leadership Academy in [[Pudong]].<ref name=Who>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U246705|title=Adair, John Eric|work=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who 2009]] (online edition)| publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=December 2008|accessdate=19 January 2009}}</ref> In 2009 he was appointed Chair of Leadership Studies United Nations System Staff College in Turin.<ref>[http://www.johnadair.co.uk/ John Adair's website]</ref> He is President of Adair International.

