[[File:Berkeley Wells Fargo.jpg|thumb|Wells Fargo [[branch (banking)|branch]] in [[Berkeley, California]]]]

'''Wells Fargo & Company''' is an American multinational [[financial services]] company headquartered in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], with central offices throughout the United States.<ref name="Wells-Fargo-&-Company-Feb-2009-10-K">{{cite web|url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/867/95013409003967/filing-main.htm |title=Wells Fargo & Company, Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date Feb 27, 2009 |publisher=secdatabase.com |accessdate =May 13, 2018}}</ref> It is the [[List of largest banks|world's second-largest bank]] by [[market capitalization]] and the [[List of largest banks in the United States|fourth largest bank in the US]] by total assets.<ref name=BankCap/><ref name=Fortune>{{cite news| url= http://fortune.com/2015/07/23/wells-fargo-worlds-most-valuable-bank/ | work=Fortune| title= This is the most valuable bank in the world|accessdate=24 July 2015}}</ref> Wells Fargo is ranked #26 on the 2018 [[Fortune 500]] rankings of the largest US corporations by total revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/list/|title=Fortune 500 Companies 2018: Who Made the List|website=Fortune|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-09}}</ref> In July 2015, Wells Fargo became the world's largest bank by market capitalization, edging past [[ICBC]],<ref name="Fortune"/> before slipping behind [[JPMorgan Chase]] in September 2016, in the wake of a scandal involving the creation of over [[Wells Fargo account fraud scandal|2 million fake bank accounts]] by Wells Fargo employees.<ref name=BankCap>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-09-13/wells-fargo-eclipsed-by-jpmorgan-as-world-s-most-valuable-bank|title=Wells Fargo Eclipsed by JPMorgan as World's Most Valuable Bank|author=Laura J. Keller and Katherine Chiglinsky|publisher=Bloomberg L.P|date=September 13, 2016|accessdate=September 16, 2016}}</ref> Wells Fargo surpassed [[Citigroup]] to become the third-largest US bank by assets at the end of 2015 but fell behind [[Bank of America]] to third in bank deposits in 2017.<ref name=WellsFargoMidwestClosures2/>

The firm's primary operating subsidiary is [[national bank]] '''Wells Fargo Bank, N.A.''', which designates its main office as [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota]]. Wells Fargo in its present form is a result of a merger between San Francisco–based Wells Fargo & Company and [[Minneapolis]]-based [[Norwest Corporation]] in 1998 and the subsequent 2008 acquisition of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]-based [[Wachovia]]. Following the mergers, the company transferred its headquarters to Wells Fargo's headquarters in San Francisco and merged its operating subsidiary with Wells Fargo's operating subsidiary in Sioux Falls. Along with JPMorgan Chase, Bank of America, and Citigroup, Wells Fargo is one of the "[[Big Four (banking)#United States|Big Four Banks]]" of the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.federalreserve.gov/releases/lbr/current/|title=FRB: Large Commercial Banks-- March 31, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> {{As of|2018|06}}, it had 8,050 [[branches]] and 13,000 [[automated teller machines|ATM]]s.<ref name="WF Quarterly Fact Sheet 2Q2018" /> In 2018 the company had operations in 35 countries with over 70 million customers globally.<ref name="WF Quarterly Fact Sheet 2Q2018" />

In February 2014, Wells Fargo was named the world's most valuable bank brand for the second consecutive year<ref>{{cite web |title= Wells Fargo Tops List of World's Most Valuable Bank Brands, Leads Strong US Growth|url=http://brandfinance.com/news/in_the_news/wells-fargo-tops-list-of-worlds-most-valuable-bank-brands-leads-strong-us-growth |publisher=Brand Finance|date=February 3, 2014}}</ref> in ''[[The Banker]]'' and [[Brand Finance]] study of the top 500 banking brands.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Top 500 Banking Brands, 2014|url=http://www.thebanker.com/Banker-Data/Banker-Rankings/The-Top-500-Banking-Brands-2014 |publisher=The Banker|date=February 3, 2014}}</ref> In 2016, Wells Fargo ranked 7th on the [[Forbes Magazine]] [[Forbes Global 2000|Global 2000]] list of largest public companies in the world and ranked 27th on the [[Fortune 500]] list of the largest companies in the US.<ref name=wellsfargotoday/><ref name="CNN">{{cite web|url=http://beta.fortune.com/fortune500/wells-fargo-27|title=Fortune 500 #30: Wells Fargo|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=[[Fortune Magazine]]|access-date=|accessdate=July 24, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, the company was ranked the 22nd most admired company in the world, and the 7th most respected company in the world.<ref name=wellsfargotoday/> {{As of|2018|12}}, the company had a [[Standard & Poors]] [[credit rating]] of A−.<ref name="Credit ratings Q32018" /> However, for a brief period in 2007, the company was the only AAA&#x2011;rated bank, reflecting the highest credit rating from two firms.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/wells-fargo-bank-becomes-sps-only-aaa-credit-rated-us-bank-57919847.html | title=Wells Fargo Bank Becomes S&P's Only "AAA" Credit-rated U.S. Bank | publisher=[[PRNewswire]] | date=February 14, 2007}}</ref> 

On February 2, 2018, the [[US Federal Reserve Bank]] barred Wells Fargo from growing its nearly [[US$]]2 trillion-asset base any further, based upon years of misconduct, until Wells Fargo fixes its internal problems to the satisfaction of the Federal Reserve.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/business/wells-fargo-federal-reserve.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&clickSource=story-heading&module=first-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news|title=Federal Reserve Shackles Wells Fargo After Fraud Scandal|author=Emily Flitter, Binyamin Appelbaum, and Stacy Cowley|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 2, 2018|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> In April 2018, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that the [[US Department of Labor]] had launched a probe into whether Wells Fargo was pushing its customers into more expensive [[retirement plans in the United States|retirement plans]] as well as into [[retirement fund]]s managed by Wells Fargo itself.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/wells-fargos-401-k-practices-probed-by-labor-department-1524757138|title=Wells Fargo’s 401(k) Practices Probed by Labor Department|author=Gretchen Morgenson and Emily Glazer|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=April 26, 2018|accessdate=April 26, 2018|quote=Department is examining if bank pushed participants in low-cost 401(k) plans into more expensive IRAs}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/26/labor-department-is-investigating-wells-fargos-401k-unit-wsj.html|title=Labor Department is reportedly investigating Wells Fargo's 401(k) unit|author=Kate Rooney|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=April 26, 2018|accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref> Subsequently in May 2018, ''The Wall Street Journal'' reported that Wells Fargo's business banking group had improperly altered documents about business clients in 2017 and early 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/05/17/news/companies/wells-fargo-alter-documents/index.html|title=Wells Fargo altered documents about business clients|author=Matt Egan|publisher=CNN|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, Wells Fargo began retreating from [[retail banking]] in the [[Midwestern United States]] by announcing the sale of all its physical bank branch locations in [[Indiana]], [[Michigan]], and [[Ohio]] to [[Flagstar Bank]].<ref name=WellsFargoMidwestClosures1>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/06/05/news/companies/wells-fargo-sells-branches-indiana-michigan/index.html|title=Wells Fargo sells all its branches in three Midwestern states|author=Matt Egan|publisher=CNN|date=June 5, 2018|accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=WellsFargoMidwestClosures2>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-05/wells-fargo-sells-all-its-branches-in-indiana-michigan-ohio|title=Wells Fargo sells all its branches in Indiana, Michigan, Ohio|author=Hannah Levitt|publisher=Bloomberg, L.P|date=June 5, 2018|accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref>

==History==
{{Main article|History of Wells Fargo}}

===Wells Fargo History Museums===
The company operates 12 museums, most known as a [[Wells Fargo History Museum]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellsfargohistory.com/museums/|title=Museums - Wells Fargo History|publisher=}}</ref> in its corporate buildings in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], [[Denver, Colorado]], [[Des Moines, Iowa]], [[Los Angeles, California]], [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], [[Phoenix, Arizona]], [[Portland, Oregon]], [[Sacramento, California]] and [[San Francisco, California]]. Displays include original [[stagecoach]]es, photographs, gold nuggets and mining artifacts, the Pony Express, [[telegraph]] equipment and historic bank artifacts. The company also operates a museum about company history in the [[Pony Express Terminal]] in [[Old Sacramento State Historic Park]] in [[Sacramento, California]], which was the company's second office,<ref>{{cite web|title=B.F. Hastings Building|url=http://www.csrmf.org/visitor-information/other-california-state-park-sattractions-in-old-sacramento/bf-hastings-building|publisher=California State Railroad Museum Foundation|accessdate=24 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213025053/http://www.csrmf.org/visitor-information/other-california-state-park-sattractions-in-old-sacramento/bf-hastings-building|archive-date=February 13, 2015|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the Wells Fargo History Museum in [[Old Town San Diego State Historic Park]] in [[San Diego, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Old Town State Historic Park i|url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/links/oldtown.htm|publisher=San Diego History Center|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>

Wells Fargo operates the Alaska Heritage Museum in [[Anchorage, Alaska]], which features a large collection of Alaskan Native artifacts, [[ivory]] carvings and baskets, fine art by Alaskan artists, and displays about Wells Fargo history in the [[Alaskan Gold Rush]] era.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wellsfargohistory.com/museums/anchorage/|title=Alaska Museum - Wells Fargo History|publisher=}}</ref>

===Key dates===
[[File:Apache Junction-Superstition Mountain Museum-Wells Fargo Bank.JPG|thumb|A late 19th Century Wells Fargo Bank in Apache Junction, Arizona]][[File:Phoenix-Wells Fargo Museum-1860 Wells fargo Stagecoach.jpg|thumb|1879 Wells Fargo Stagecoach on exhibit in the Wells Fargo Museum in Phoenix]][[File:Black Canyon City-Wells Fargo Stage Stop-1872.jpg|thumb|The Wells Fargo Stage Stop built in 1872 in [[List of historic properties in Black Canyon City, Arizona|Black Canyon City, Arizona]]]]
[[File:WellsFargoChinatownHoustonnew.JPG|thumb|Wells Fargo bank in [[Chinatown, Houston|Chinatown]], [[Houston]], Texas]]
[[File:Wells Fargo in Fort Worth, TX.png|thumb|A remodeled Wells Fargo bank in [[Fort Worth, Texas]]]] 
[[File:Wells Fargo in Laredo, TX IMG 1054.JPG|thumb|Wells Fargo in [[Laredo, Texas|Laredo]], Texas]]
* 1852: [[Henry Wells]] and [[William Fargo|William G. Fargo]], the two founders of [[American Express]], formed Wells Fargo & Company to provide express and banking services to California.
* 1860: Wells Fargo gained control of [[Butterfield Overland Mail]] Company, leading to operation of the western portion of the [[Pony Express]].
* 1866: "Grand consolidation" united Wells Fargo, Holladay, and Overland Mail stage lines under the Wells Fargo name.
* 1905: Wells Fargo separated its banking and express operations; Wells Fargo's bank was merged with the Nevada National Bank to form the Wells Fargo Nevada National Bank.
* 1918: As a wartime measure, the [[US Federal Government]] nationalized Wells Fargo's express franchise into a [[Federal agencies of the United States|federal agency]] known as the US [[Railway Express Agency]]. The US Federal Government took control of the express company. The bank began rebuilding but with a focus on commercial markets. After the war, REA was privatized and continued service until 1975.
* 1923: Wells Fargo Nevada merged with the Union Trust Company to form the Wells Fargo Bank & Union Trust Company.
* 1929: Northwest Bancorporation was formed as a banking association.
* 1954: Wells Fargo & Union Trust shortened its name to Wells Fargo Bank.
* 1960: Wells Fargo merged with American Trust Company to form the Wells Fargo Bank American Trust Company.
* 1962: Wells Fargo American Trust again shortened its name to Wells Fargo Bank.
* 1968: Wells Fargo converted to a federal banking charter, becoming Wells Fargo Bank, N.A.
* 1969: Wells Fargo & Company holding company was formed, with Wells Fargo Bank as its main subsidiary.
* 1982: Northwest Bancorporation acquired consumer finance firm Dial Finance which is renamed Norwest Financial Service the following year.
* 1983: Northwest Bancorporation was renamed [[Norwest Corporation]].
* 1983: [[White Eagle (robbery)|White Eagle]], largest US bank heist to date took place at a Wells Fargo depot in [[West Hartford, Connecticut]].
* 1986: Wells Fargo acquired [[Crocker National Bank|Crocker National Corporation]] from [[Midland Bank]].
* 1987: Wells Fargo acquired the personal trust business of [[Bank of America]].
* 1988: Wells Fargo acquired Barclays Bank of California from [[Barclays plc]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/01/16/business/company-news-wells-fargo-to-buy-barclays-in-california.html | title=Wells Fargo to Buy Barclays in California | author=Lawrence M. Fisher | publisher=[[New York Times]] | date=January 16, 1988}}</ref>
* 1995: Wells Fargo became the first major US financial services firm to offer Internet banking.
* 1996: Wells Fargo acquired [[First Interstate Bancorp]] for US$11.6 billion.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/01/25/business/wells-fargo-wins-battle-for-first-interstate.html | title=Wells Fargo Wins Battle for First Interstate | author=Saul Hansell | publisher=[[New York Times]] | date=January 25, 1996}}</ref>
* 1998: Wells Fargo Bank was acquired by [[Norwest Corporation]] of Minneapolis.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/press/merge19980608|title=Wells Fargo and Norwest to Merge|publisher=Wellsfargo.com|date=June 8, 1998|accessdate=2012-03-13}}</ref>  (Norwest was the surviving company; however, it chose to continue business under the more well-known Wells Fargo name.)
* 2000: Wells Fargo Bank acquired [[National Bank of Alaska]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://juneauempire.com/stories/122299/Loc_bank.html | title=Wells Fargo to buy NBA | publisher=Juneau Empire | date=December 22, 1999}}</ref>
* 2000: Wells Fargo acquired [[First Security Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/press/merge19980608|title=Wells Fargo and Norwest to Merge|publisher=Wellsfargo.com|date=June 8, 1998|accessdate=2012-03-13}}</ref> 
* 2001: Wells Fargo acquired [[H.D. Vest Financial Services]] for US$128 million, but sold it in 2015 for US$580 million.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.investmentnews.com/article/20151014/FREE/151019966/h-d-vest-to-be-acquired-by-internet-company-blucora-for-580-million | title=H.D. Vest to be acquired by Internet company Blucora for $580 million | publisher=Investment News | date=October 15, 2015}}</ref>
* 2007: Wells Fargo acquired [[CIT Group|CIT]]'s construction unit.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/wells-fargo-to-acquire-cits-construction-unit-58261737.html | title=Wells Fargo to Acquire CIT's Construction Unit | publisher=[[PRNewswire]] | date=June 21, 2007}}</ref>
* 2007: Wells Fargo acquired Placer Sierra Bank.
* 2007: Wells Fargo acquired Greater Bay Bancorp, which had US$7.4 billion in assets, in a US$1.5 billion transaction.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/wells-fargo-greater-bay-bancorp-agree-to-merge-57936667.html | title=Wells Fargo, Greater Bay Bancorp Agree to Merge | publisher=[[PRNewswire]] | date=May 4, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2007/05/07/wells-fargo-gobbles-up-greater-bay-bancorp/ | title=Wells Fargo Gobbles Up Greater Bay Bancorp | publisher=[[New York Times]] | date=May 7, 2007}}</ref>
* 2008: Wells Fargo acquired United Bancorporation of Wyoming.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/eastbay/stories/2008/01/14/daily23.html | title=Wells to acquire United Bancorp of Wyoming | publisher=[[San Francisco Business Times]] | date=January 15, 2008}}</ref>
* 2008: Wells Fargo acquired Century Bancshares of Texas.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bizjournals.com/dallas/stories/2008/08/11/daily50.html?page=all | title=Wells Fargo to acquire Century Bank | date=August 13, 2008 | publisher=[[Dallas Business Journal]] | author=Chad Eric Watt | accessdate=February 2, 2015}}</ref>
* 2008: Wells Fargo acquired [[Wachovia]] Corporation.
* 2009: Wells Fargo acquired North Coast Surety Insurance Services.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUS201910+17-Apr-2009+BW20090417 | title=Wells Fargo Acquires North Coast Surety Insurance Services | publisher=[[Business Wire]] | work=[[Reuters]] | date=April 17, 2009}}</ref>
* 2012: Wells Fargo acquired Merlin Securities.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/about/press/2012/20120425_WellsFargotoAcquireMerlin/ | title=Wells Fargo to Acquire Merlin Securities, LLC | publisher=Wells Fargo | date=April 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/04/27/wells-fargo-to-buy-prime-brokerage/ | title=Wells Fargo to Buy Prime Brokerage Firm | publisher=[[New York Times]] | date=April 27, 2012}}</ref>
* 2012: Wells Fargo acquired stake in The Rock Creek Group LP.

===Wachovia acquisition===
[[File:2011-11-22 Wells Fargo ATMs lit at night.jpg|thumb|A former Wachovia branch converted to Wells Fargo in the fall of 2011 in [[Durham, North Carolina]]]]
On October 3, 2008, [[Wachovia]] agreed to be bought by Wells Fargo for about US$14.8 billion in an all-stock transaction. This news came four days after the US [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]] (FDIC) made moves to have [[Citigroup]] buy Wachovia for US$2.1 billion. Citigroup protested Wachovia's agreement to sell itself to Wells Fargo and threatened legal action over the matter. However, the deal with Wells Fargo overwhelmingly won shareholder approval since it valued Wachovia at about seven times what Citigroup offered. To further ensure shareholder approval, Wachovia issued Wells Fargo preferred stock that holds 39.9% of the voting power in the company.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/economy/2008-10-03-378872640_x.htm | title=Wells Fargo agrees to buy Wachovia; Citi objects | publisher=[[USA Today]] | work=[[Associated Press]] | date=October 4, 2008 | accessdate=October 4, 2008}}</ref>

On October 4, 2008, a New York state judge issued a temporary injunction blocking the transaction from going forward while the situation was sorted out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc7ny.com/archive/6432867/ | title=Court tilts Wachovia fight toward Wells | date=October 5, 2008 | accessdate=October 5, 2008}}</ref> Citigroup alleged that they had an exclusivity agreement with Wachovia that barred Wachovia from negotiating with other potential buyers. The injunction was overturned late in the evening on October 5, 2008, by New York state appeals court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biz.yahoo.com/ap/081005/wells_fargo_wachovia.html?.v=29|title=Court tilts Wachovia fight toward Wells Fargo}}{{dead link|date=March 2012}}</ref> Citigroup and Wells Fargo then entered into negotiations brokered by the FDIC to reach an amicable solution to the impasse. Those negotiations failed. Sources say that Citigroup was unwilling to take on more risk than the US$42 billion that would have been the cap under the previous FDIC-backed deal (with the FDIC incurring all losses over US$42 billion). Citigroup did not block the merger, but indicated they would seek damages of US$60 billion for breach of an alleged exclusivity agreement with Wachovia.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/money/economy/2008-10-09-2208148309_x.htm | title=Wells Fargo plans to buy Wachovia; Citi ends talks | publisher=[[USA Today]] | work=[[Associated Press]] | date=October 9, 2008 | accessdate=October 11, 2008}}</ref>

===Investment by US Treasury Department during 2008 financial crisis===
On October 28, 2008, Wells Fargo was the recipient of US$25 billion of Emergency Economic Stabilization Act funds in the form of a preferred stock purchase by the [[US Treasury Department]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/scribd/?item_id=519794&filepath=/docs/historical/fct/treasury/treasury_tarp_transreport_20081117.pdf | title= Capital Purchase Program Transaction Report | date=November 17, 2008 | accessdate=January 4, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Landler, Mark |author2=Dash, Eric |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Drama Behind a $250&nbsp;billion Banking Deal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/15/business/economy/15bailout.html|date=October 15, 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 4, 2009}}</ref> Tests by the US Federal Government revealed that Wells Fargo needed an additional US$13.7 billion in order to remain well capitalized if the economy were to deteriorate further under stress test scenarios. On May 11, 2009, Wells Fargo announced an additional stock offering which was completed on May 13, 2009, raising US$8.6 billion in capital. The remaining US$4.9 billion in capital was planned to be raised through earnings. On Dec. 23, 2009, Wells Fargo redeemed the US$25 billion of preferred stock issued to the US Treasury. As part of the redemption of the preferred stock, Wells Fargo also paid accrued dividends of US$131.9 million, bringing the total dividends paid to US$1.441 billion since the preferred stock was issued in October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/press/2009/20091223_tarp_repayment|title=News Releases|publisher=Wells Fargo|date=December 18, 2009|accessdate=December 30, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406010401/https://www.wellsfargo.com/press/2009/20091223_tarp_repayment|archive-date=April 6, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

====History of Wells Fargo Securities====
Wells Fargo Securities was established in 2009 to house Wells Fargo's capital markets group which it obtained during the Wachovia acquisition. Prior to that point, Wells Fargo had little to no participation in investment banking activities, though Wachovia had a well established investment banking practice which it operated under the [[Wachovia Securities]] banner.

Wachovia's institutional capital markets and investment banking business arose from the merger of Wachovia and First Union. First Union had bought [[Bowles Hollowell Connor & Co.]] on April 30, 1998 adding to its [[merger and acquisition]], [[high yield]], [[leveraged finance]], equity underwriting, [[private placement]], [[loan syndication]], [[risk management]], and [[public finance]] capabilities.<ref>{{cite press release | url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/first-union-to-expand-investment-banking-capabilities-with-acquisition-of-bowles-hollowell-conner-77048217.html | title=First Union To Expand Investment Banking Capabilities With Acquisition Of Bowles Hollowell Conner | publisher=[[PRNewswire]] | date=March 10, 1998}}</ref>

Legacy components of Wells Fargo Securities include [[Wachovia Securities]], [[Bowles Hollowell Connor & Co.]], Barrington Associates, [[Halsey, Stuart & Co.]], [[Bache & Co.|Leopold Cahn & Co.]], [[Bache & Co.]]. [[Prudential Securities]], [[A.G. Edwards, Inc.]] and the investment banking arm of [[Citadel LLC]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ahmed|first=Azam|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/08/15/wells-fargo-brings-aboard-citadels-investment-banking-unit/|title=Date 15 Aug 2011 |publisher=Dealbook.nytimes.com|date=August 15, 2011|accessdate=2012-03-13}}</ref>

[[Image:Duke Energy Center cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Duke Energy Center]] in Charlotte, North Carolina home of Wells Fargo Securities<ref>{{cite web|last=Rothacker|first=Rick|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2011/08/04/2502300/wells-fargo-securities-to-occupy.html#storylink=misearch|title=Wells Fargo Securities to occupy new uptown space &#124; CharlotteObserver.com & The Charlotte Observer Newspaper|publisher=Charlotteobserver.com|date=2011-08-04|accessdate=2012-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111105062856/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/2011/08/04/2502300/wells-fargo-securities-to-occupy.html#storylink=misearch|archive-date=November 5, 2011|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref>]]

===Environmental record===

In 2009, Wells Fargo ranked #1 among banks and insurance companies, and #13 overall, in [[Newsweek Magazine]]’s inaugural "Green Rankings" of the country’s 500 largest companies.<ref>{{cite news |title=Newsweek: HP top 'green' company |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2009/09/21/daily90.html |last=<!--no byline--> |work=[[Silicon Valley Business Journal]] |date=September 25, 2009 |accessdate=May 13, 2018 |url-access=registration }}</ref> In 2013, the company was recognized by the EPA Center for Corporate Climate Leadership as a Climate Leadership Award winner, in the category "Excellence in Greenhouse Gas Management (Goal Setting Certificate)"; this recognition was for the company's aim to reduce its absolute [[greenhouse gas emissions]] from its US operations by 35% by 2020 versus 2008 levels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epa.gov/climateleadership/2013-climate-leadership-award-winners#Wells%20Fargo%20&%20Company|title=2013 Climate Leadership Award Winners|last=<!--no byline-->|date=March 1, 2013|website=EPA Center for Corporate Climate Leadership|publisher=[[US Environmental Protection Agency]]|access-date=May 13, 2018}}</ref>

{{As of|2013}}, Wells Fargo had provided more than {{US$|6 billion}} in financing for environmentally beneficial business opportunities, including supporting 185 commercial-scale solar photovoltaic projects and 27 utility-scale wind projects nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wells Fargo mortgage consultant team joins Century 21 Ludecke, Inc. |url=http://www.monroviaweekly.com/lifestyle/home-garden/real-estate/wells-fargo-mortgage-consultant-team-joins-century-21-ludecke-inc/ | publisher=[[Monrovia Weekly]] | date=January 22, 2013 | accessdate=May 13, 2018 }}</ref>{{better source|date=May 2018}}

Wells Fargo has launched what it believes to be the first blog among its industry peers to report on its environmental stewardship and to solicit feedback and ideas from its stakeholders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.wellsfargo.com/environment/index.html |title=Wells Fargo Environmental Forum |publisher=Blog.wellsfargo.com |accessdate=June 12, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616045103/http://blog.wellsfargo.com/environment/index.html |archive-date=June 16, 2010 |dead-url=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref><!--this link is archived in both archive.org and archive.is, but it is a link to the blog as a whole, not to a specific posting--><ref name="Business Wire: Wells Fargo Launches Environmental Stewardship Blog">{{cite press release |title=Wells Fargo Launches Environmental Stewardship Blog |url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20100407006345/en/Wells-Fargo-Launches-Environmental-Stewardship-Blog |publisher=Wells Fargo |accessdate=May 13, 2018 |date=April 7, 2010 |via=Business Wire }}</ref>

{{quote|"<!--NB: This is a quote within a quote-->We want to be as open and clear as possible about our environmental efforts – both our accomplishments and challenges – and share our experiences, ideas and thoughts as we work to integrate environmental responsibility into everything we do," said Mary Wenzel, director of Environmental Affairs. "We also want to hear and learn from our customers. By working together, we can do even more to protect and preserve natural resources for future generations."|sign=Mary Wenzel, director of Environmental Affairs, Wells Fargo|source=2010 press release}}

==Operations and services==
[[File:Wells Fargo footprint.png|thumb|Map of Wells Fargo branches in August 2015]]

Wells Fargo delineates three different business segments when reporting results: [[Retail banking|Community Banking]]; [[Wholesale Banking]]; and Wealth, Brokerage and Retirement.

===Community banking===
The Community Banking segment includes Regional Banking, Diversified Products, and Consumer Deposits groups, as well as Wells Fargo Customer Connection (formerly Wells Fargo Phone Bank, Wachovia Direct Access, the National Business Banking Center, and Credit Card Customer Service). Wells Fargo also has around 2,000 stand-alone mortgage branches throughout the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.responsiblelending.org/mortgage-lending/research-analysis/ip004-Wells_Fargo-0404.pdf|title=A Review of Wells Fargo's Subprime Lending|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> There are mini-branches located inside of other buildings, which are almost exclusively grocery stores, that usually contain ATMs, basic [[bank teller|teller]] services, and, space permitting, an office for private meetings with customers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/locator/atm/home|title=Click "Wells Fargo In-Store Branches" for a pop-up with this information|publisher=Wellsfargo.com|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref> In March 2017, Wells Fargo announced a plan to offer smartphone-based transactions with mobile wallets including Wells Fargo Wallet, Android Pay and Samsung Pay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/27/wells-fargo-lets-you-use-apple-pay-and-android-pay-to-withdraw-money/|title=Wells Fargo will let you use Apple Pay and Android Pay to withdraw money|publisher=TechCrunch|author=Romain Dillet|date=27 March 2017|access-date=29 March 2017}}</ref>

====Consumer lending====
As of Q3 2011, Wells Fargo Home Mortgage was the largest retail mortgage lender in the United States, originating one out of every four home loans.<ref>Q3 2011, Inside Mortgage Finance, Sept. 2011{{full citation needed|date=June 2012}}</ref> Wells Fargo services US$1.8 trillion in home mortgages, the second largest servicing portfolio in the US<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wellsfargo.com/invest_relations/annual |title=Browser Warning|publisher=Wellsfargo.com|accessdate=2012-03-13}}</ref> It was reported in 2012 Wells Fargo reached 30% market share for US mortgages, however, the then-CEO [[John Stumpf]] had said the numbers were misleading because about half of that share represented the aggregation of smaller loans that were then sold on in the secondary market. In 2013, its share was closer to 22%; of which eight percentage points was aggregation.<ref name="euromoney1">{{cite news|title=Bank of the Year: How Wells Fargo conquered America |publisher=Euromoney |date=July 2013|url=http://www.euromoney.com/Article/3229317/Category/17/ChannelPage/0/Bank-of-the-Year-How-Wells-Fargo-conquered-America.html}}</ref>

====Wells Fargo private student loans====
Wells Fargo private student loans are available to students to pay for college expenses, such as tuition, books, computers, or housing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nerdwallet.com/blog/loans/student-loans/wells-fargo-student-loan-review/|title=Wells Fargo Private Student Loan Review — NerdWallet|date=2016-06-09|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-25}}</ref> Loans are available for [[undergraduate education|undergraduate]], career and [[community colleges]], [[graduate school]], law school and medical school. Wells Fargo also provides private student loan consolidation and student loans for parents.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}

====Equipment lending====
Wells Fargo has various divisions that finance and lease equipment to different types of companies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=4277204|title=Wells Fargo Equipment Finance, Inc.: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-05-14}}</ref> {{Needs citation|date=May 2018}} One venture is [[Wells Fargo Rail]], which in 2015 agreed to the purchase of [[GE Capital Rail Services]] and merged in with [[First Union Rail]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-30/wells-fargo-agrees-to-buy-general-electric-railcar-leasing-unit|title=Wells Fargo Agrees to Acquire GE's Railcar Leasing Business|date=2015-09-30|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en}}</ref> In late 2015, it was announced that Wells Fargo would buy three GE units focused on business loans equipment financing. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-wells-fargo-ge-20151014-story.html|title=Wells Fargo buys 3 GE units focused on equipment financing|last=Koren|first=James Rufus|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-05-14}}</ref>

===Wealth and Investment Management===
[[File:Wells Fargo Advisors headguarters.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Wells Fargo Advisors headquarters in [[St. Louis]], Missouri]]

Wells Fargo offers investment products through its subsidiaries, Wells Fargo Investments, LLC and Wells Fargo Advisors, LLC, as well as through national broker/dealer firms. Mutual funds are offered under the Wells Fargo Advantage Funds brand name. The company also serves high-net-worth individuals through its [[private banking|private bank]] and [[Wealth management|family wealth]] group.
[[File:Wells Fargo Advisors.svg|alt=|thumb|The logo for Wells Fargo Advisors]]
[[Wells Fargo Advisors]] is the [[brokerage]] subsidiary of Wells Fargo, located in [[St. Louis]], Missouri. It is the third largest brokerage firm in the United States as of the third quarter of 2010 with US$1.1&nbsp;trillion retail client assets under management.<ref name=wellsfargotoday/>

Wells Fargo Advisors was known as [[Wachovia Securities]] until May 1, 2009, when it legally changed names following the Wells Fargo's acquisition of [[Wachovia Corporation]].

In September 2018, Wells Fargo announced to cut 26,450 jobs by 2020 to reduce costs by US$4 billion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/wells-fargo-job-cuts_us_5ba4aecae4b0181540dbd52d|title=Wells Fargo Plans To Eliminate Up To 26,450 Jobs By 2020|last=Reuters|date=2018-09-21|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-10-01|language=en-US}}</ref>

====Wells Fargo Securities====
{{Infobox company
| name = Wells Fargo Securities, LLC
| logo = [[Image:Wells Fargo Securities Logo.svg|200px]]
| type = Subsidiary
| location_city = [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]
| area_served = Worldwide
